// DESIRED (known-red capture): an array literal `{…}` typed `[N]i64` (any non-char element) must compile
// with i64 elements. Today it is MISCOMPILED to `[N x i8]` (the element `1000` > 255 proves the width — an
// i8 store truncates/overflows it). The root is NOT just codegen: an array literal is only typed `[N]i64`
// in a RETURN context; in an assignment (`a: [2]i64; a = {1000,2}`) semantic defaults it to char/i8, so its
// `resolved` type (and thus codegen) is i8. A full fix is multi-layer — context-sensitive literal typing in
// semantic (type the literal from its assignment/return target) → lowering `resolved` → typed codegen
// (`[N x T]` stack stores) → SHAPED_ARRAY return-by-value for the func form below. It is a type-inference
// gap, not a localized miscompile; goes GREEN once the literal tracks its declared `[2]i64`.
// RUN: %arche build -o %t %s && %t | grep -qF "ok 1000 2"
#import { fmt }

mk :: func() -> [2]i64 {
  return { 1000, 2 };
}

main :: proc() {
  a := mk();
  fmt.printf("ok %d %d\n", a[0], a[1]);
}
